    sanskrit: "अन्ये च बहव: शूरा मदर्थे त्यक्तजीविता: |\nनानाशस्त्रप्रहरणा: सर्वे युद्धविशारदा: ||",
    transliteration: "anye cha bahavaḥ śhūrā mad-arthe tyakta-jīvitāḥ\nnānā-śhastra-praharaṇāḥ sarve yuddha-viśhāradāḥ",
    translation: "There are many other heroes who are prepared to lay down their lives for my sake. All of them are equipped with different kinds of weapons, and all are experienced in military science.",
    purport: `
        <p>In this verse, Duryodhana concludes his description of his own military strength. He mentions that beyond the great names like Bhishma and Drona, there are "many other heroes" (<em>anye cha bahavaḥ śhūrā</em>) supporting him.</p>

        <p><strong>1. The Ominous Phrase "Tyakta-jīvitāḥ":</strong>
        Duryodhana uses the term <em>tyakta-jīvitāḥ</em>, which means "those who have given up their lives." While he means it as a compliment—that his soldiers are prepared to die for him—it is a slip of the tongue that foreshadows the future. In Vedic literature, it is said that what one speaks at a momentous time often comes true. Ironically, all these warriors <em>would</em> actually lose their lives because they were fighting on the side of unrighteousness.</p>

        <p><strong>2. Diverse Weaponry and Expertise:</strong>
        He describes his army as <em>nānā-śhastra-praharaṇāḥ</em>—equipped with many types of weapons (swords, maces, bows, etc.)—and <em>yuddha-viśhāradāḥ</em>, meaning they are all experts in the science of war. Duryodhana is emphasizing that his army has both the physical equipment and the mental training to win.</p>

        <p><strong>3. The "Me-Centered" Leadership:</strong>
        Note the word <em>mad-arthe</em>, which means "for my sake." This reveals Duryodhana’s selfish nature. He views this entire cosmic struggle not as a matter of principle or dharma, but as something being fought specifically for his personal ambition. This contrasts sharply with the Pandavas, who fought for the sake of Krishna and Dharma.</p>

        <p><strong>Conclusion:</strong>
        Verse 9 teaches us about The Cost of Loyalty. It is a reminder that being "talented" or "well-equipped" is not the same as being "right." You can have a team of experts with the best tools in the world, but if the goal (the <em>why</em>) is purely selfish, the ultimate result is often destruction. Duryodhana’s boastful words actually serve as a tragic eulogy for the millions of men about to die for his ego.</p>
    `
